and train an air force en masse to counter the global conquest of Nazi Germany and Imperial Japan. More than fifteen thousand American airmen and, in some cases, women burned, crashed, or fell to their deaths in stateside training accidents during the war–their lives and stories shuffled away in piles of Air Force bureaucracy.The forgotten story of Getaway Gertie was originally inspired by summer evenings around the campfire on the shores of Lake Ontario, where parts of the plane have washed up. Building on those campfire tales, Wilber deftly connects myth with fact and memory with historicity. The result is a vivid portrait of the forgotten soldier of the home front and a new take on the meaning of wartime sacrifice as the last survivors of the Greatest Generation pass away.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aAircraft accidentszOntario, Lake, Region (N.Y. and Ont.)xHistoryy20th century. 0aAircraft accidents. 0aAirplanes, MilitaryxAccidentsxInvestigationzOntario, Lake, Region (N.Y. and Ont.). 0aAirplanes, MilitaryxAccidentsxInvestigation. 0aAirplanes, MilitaryxAccidentszOntario, Lake, Region (N.Y. and Ont.)xHistory. 0aAirplanes, MilitaryxAccidents. 0aB-24 (Bomber). 0aWorld War, 1939-1945xAerial operations, American. 0aWorld War, 1939-1945zNew York (State). 4aMilitary History. 4aWorld War II. 7aHISTORY / Military / World War II.2bisacsh  aGetaway Gertie, lost plane in Lake Ontario, B-24 bomber, New York wreck-seeking, NOAA marine sanctuary, Liberator bomber, home front USAAF training deaths.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCornell University Press Complete eBook-Package 2023z978311075183308iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2023 Englishz978311131929208iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2023z9783